title:	feat(wtf): refactor classifier to producer-consumer architecture with worker pool
state:	open
author:	brbaker-alog
labels:	
comments:	0
assignees:	
--
## Summary

Refactor the WTF classifier from pull-based polling to a producer-consumer architecture with a dedicated worker pool. This decouples entry discovery from classification execution, provides natural concurrency control, and makes system behavior more observable and predictable.

## Context

The current classifier implementation (#24) uses a single-threaded pull model where the main loop fetches an entry, classifies it, writes the result, then repeats. This design:
- Couples discovery to execution (can't parallelize)
- Provides no visibility into work backlog
- Has no natural backpressure mechanism
- Makes concurrency control a special case rather than the norm

The producer-consumer pattern inverts this: one task feeds a queue (producer), N workers consume from it (consumers). This gives natural concurrency control, observable queue depth, and separation of concerns.

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Add module-level queue and configuration

**File:** `mcp-server/classifier/worker.ts`

At module level, add:

```typescript
// Queue and worker pool configuration
const classificationQueue: Array<RawEntryRow> = [];
const WORKER_POOL_SIZE = 3;
const MAX_QUEUE_DEPTH_WARNING = 100;
```

### 2. Implement the producer function

The producer polls the database and feeds the queue. Replace the current single-loop logic.

```typescript
/**
 * Producer: polls DB for unclassified entries and feeds the queue.
 */
async function producer(
  dbPath: string | undefined,
  pollIntervalMs: number,
  running: () => boolean
): Promise<void> {
  while (running()) {
    try {
      const db = getDb(dbPath);

      // Fetch a batch of unclassified entries
      const rows = db
        .query(
          `SELECT r.* FROM raw_entries r
           LEFT JOIN distilled_entries d ON r.id = d.raw_id
           WHERE d.id IS NULL
           ORDER BY r.id ASC
           LIMIT 10`
        )
        .all() as RawEntryRow[];

      if (rows.length > 0) {
        // Deduplicate: only add entries not already in queue
        const queueIds = new Set(classificationQueue.map((e) => e.id));
        const newRows = rows.filter((r) => !queueIds.has(r.id));

        if (newRows.length > 0) {
          classificationQueue.push(...newRows);
          console.log(
            `[PRODUCER] Queued ${newRows.length} entries (depth: ${classificationQueue.length})`
          );

          // Emit warning if queue depth exceeds threshold
          if (classificationQueue.length >= MAX_QUEUE_DEPTH_WARNING) {
            console.warn(
              `[PRODUCER] ⚠️  Queue depth is ${classificationQueue.length} (threshold: ${MAX_QUEUE_DEPTH_WARNING}). System may be under heavy load.`
            );
          }
        }
      }

      await sleep(pollIntervalMs);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("[PRODUCER] Error in producer loop:", err);
      await sleep(pollIntervalMs);
    }
  }
}
```

### 3. Implement the consumer function

Each consumer pops from the queue, classifies, and writes results.

```typescript
/**
 * Consumer: processes entries from the queue.
 */
async function consumer(
  workerId: number,
  dbPath: string | undefined,
  rateLimitMs: number,
  running: () => boolean
): Promise<void> {
  while (running()) {
    const row = classificationQueue.shift();

    if (!row) {
      // Queue empty - sleep briefly and retry
      await sleep(100);
      continue;
    }

    console.log(
      `[WORKER ${workerId}] Processing entry ${row.id} (queue depth: ${classificationQueue.length})`
    );

    try {
      const prompt = buildClassifierPrompt({
        id: row.id,
        gen_type: row.gen_type,
        action_type: row.action_type,
        text: row.text,
        tool_name: row.tool_name,
        tool_input: row.tool_input,
        tool_response: row.tool_response,
        tool_use_id: row.tool_use_id,
      });

      const result = await classifyEntry(prompt);

      if (!result) {
        console.error(
          `[WORKER ${workerId}] Failed to classify entry ${row.id}, skipping.`
        );
        await sleep(rateLimitMs);
        continue;
      }

      const isNoise = result.action_type === "noise" ? 1 : 0;
      const db = getDb(dbPath);

      db.run(
        `INSERT INTO distilled_entries
         (raw_id, incident_id, ts, action_type, summary, is_noise)
         VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)`,
        [
          row.id,
          row.incident_id,
          row.ts,
          result.action_type,
          result.summary,
          isNoise,
        ]
      );

      await sleep(rateLimitMs);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error(`[WORKER ${workerId}] Error processing entry ${row.id}:`, err);
      await sleep(rateLimitMs);
    }
  }
}
```

### 4. Refactor `startClassifier` to launch producer + worker pool

Replace the existing single-loop implementation:

```typescript
export function startClassifier(
  dbPath?: string,
  options?: ClassifierOptions
): { stop: () => void } {
  const pollIntervalMs = options?.pollIntervalMs ?? 5000;
  const rateLimitMs = options?.rateLimitMs ?? 2000;

  let running = true;
  const isRunning = () => running;

  // Launch producer
  producer(dbPath, pollIntervalMs, isRunning);

  // Launch worker pool
  for (let i = 0; i < WORKER_POOL_SIZE; i++) {
    consumer(i, dbPath, rateLimitMs, isRunning);
  }

  console.log(
    `[CLASSIFIER] Started with ${WORKER_POOL_SIZE} workers (poll: ${pollIntervalMs}ms, rate-limit: ${rateLimitMs}ms)`
  );

  return {
    stop: () => {
      running = false;
      console.log("[CLASSIFIER] Stopped");
    },
  };
}
```

### 5. Update types if necessary

Ensure `RawEntryRow` interface is accessible to producer/consumer functions.

